CAPE TOWN - Residents of Bellville south are afraid that gangsters will soon take over their neighbourhood if there's no intervention from the South African Police Service (SAPS). Community members said that gang shootings on weekends had increased, with no police vans in sight. In 2017, the Bellville South Police Station was one of the police stations in the country where guns and ammunition went missing. Community members in the area believe these guns are allegedly being used by criminals. The residents reached out to Eyewitness News to tell their story, hoping that national government would intervene. "A few months back we had a group of gangs murdering a person. This person lives across the road from me. We have gangs shooting on each other," said resident Natano Hines. "We had someone that was hit with an axeâ€¦ we had someone who was hit with the back of a shotgun," he continued. He has accused police of not doing anything, but SAPS spokesperson Joseph Swartbooi has refuted these claims, urging community members to contact their local police commander to air their grievances. Meanwhile, the Western Cape local government said that it would continue to engage with the national police commissioner to assist citizens in the province where there was a need for policing. One community in Cape Town has urged government to urgently intervene in crime-fighting initiatives to combat crime. Bellville south is one of many areas in Cape Town battling the scourge of drug sales and gun battles between rival gangs. Western Cape Community Safety and Police Oversight MEC Reagen Allen: "I continue to maintain that we need to see significant improvement in crime intelligence. To this end, I have engaged the SA police commissioner and will continue to do so. As to our efforts to work together, we have agreed to have an open-door policy." The legislature has condemned the crimes in Bellville south. "The standing committee on community safety in the Western Cape has not visited the Belville South Police Station but we are very concerned by the increase in crime in that area and the lack of resources dedicated to that community," Allen said. The chairperson of the committee, Gillion Bosman, has called for more police resources in the area.